nd"},"en":{"1274–":"1274–Deceased","1274–Female":"1274–Deceased","1294–1370":"1294–1370","1274–Male":"1274–Deceased","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1453":"1453","1274":"1274","1294":"1294","1382":"1382","1370":"1370","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","1290":"1290","Somerset, England":"Somerset, England","Merriott, Somerset, England":"Merriott, Somerset, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Fleury","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Armand, Lucien, Yvon, Andre, Gilles, Herve, Jacques, Michel, Adrien, Benoit, Camille, Evariste.","French and English (of Norman origin): habitational name from Fleury, the name of several places in various parts of France which get their names from the Gallo-Roman personal name <i>Florus</i> (from Latin <i>florus</i> ‘blooming, flowering’) + the locative suffix <i>-acum</i>. The surname of French origin is also found in Germany. Compare   Flory  .","History: André Fleury from La Ronde-Haye in Manche, France, married Marie-Josèphe Tanguay in Saint-Vallier, QC, in 1760. — The surname was also brought to the US from Germany, having been taken there by Huguenot refugees (see   Flory  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Florey","meanings":["English: variant of   Fleury  .","Americanized form of German   Flory  .","German: altered form of French   Fleury  ."]},{"name":"Flora","meanings":["Spanish, Portuguese, and Italian; Hungarian (<b>Flóra</b>): from the female personal name <i>Flora</i>, <i>Flóra</i>, from Latin <i>flos</i>, genitive <i>floris</i> ‘flower’.","Americanized form of French   Fleury   or German   Flory  .","Czech and Polish: from a vernacular short form of the Latin personal name <i>Florianus</i> (see   Florian  )."]},{"name":"Flurry","meanings":["English: variant of   Fleury  .","Perhaps also an Americanized form of French   Fleury   or of Austrian German <b>Flöry</b> (see   Flory  )."]},{"name":"Flury","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Claus, Darrold, Fritz, Markus, Mathias.","English: variant of   Fleury  .","Swiss German: from a vernacular short form of the personal name   Florian  . In North America, this surname is also an altered form of the variant <b>Fluri</b>."]},{"name":"Flory","meanings":["English and French: variant of   Fleury   and, in North America, (also) an altered form of this.","French: from a medieval vernacular form of the Latin personal name <i>Florius</i>, a derivative of <i>Florus</i>, which is from <i>florus</i> ‘blooming, flowering’.","South German (in Austria mainly <b>Flöry</b>): from a short form of the personal name   Florian  . In part, this is a Germanized form of French   Fleury   (compare 1 above)."]}]},{"name":"Hugh","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French name, <i>Hugues</i>, <i>Hugo</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>hug</i> ‘heart, mind, spirit’. It was originally a short form of various compound names containing this element. This was borne by the aristocracy of medieval France, adopted by the Normans, and introduced by them to Britain. It was consistently one of the most popular boys' names in the Middle Ages in England, but fell out of favour in the 16th century until it was revived in the 20th century. Little Hugh of Lincoln was a child supposed in the Middle Ages to have been murdered by Jews in about  1255 , a legend responsible for several outbursts of anti-Semitism at various times. The story is referred to by  Chaucer  in The Prioress's Tale. He is not to be confused with  St Hugh of Lincoln  (  1140–1200 ), bishop of Lincoln (  1186–1200 ), who was noted for his charity and good works, his piety, and his defence of the Church against the State. Since the later Middle Ages <i>Hugh</i> has also been used as an Anglicized form of the Gaelic name Aodh ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705190,"age":16,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705191,"age":41,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705192,"age":54,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705193,"age":63,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705195,"age":108,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"Hugh Fleury was born in 1274, in Somerset, England. He married Aleonore Beauthamp in 1294, in Merriott, Somerset, England. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter."},"et":{"1274–":"1274–Surnud","1274–Female":"1274–Surnud","1294–1370":"1294–1370","1274–Male":"1274–Surnud","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1453":"1453","1274":"1274